ˆâÑQ<?php exit; ?>a:6:{s:10:"last_error";s:0:"";s:10:"last_query";s:50:"SELECT * FROM rscvd7e_posts WHERE ID = 250 LIMIT 1";s:11:"last_result";a:1:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"250";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:32:52";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:32:52";s:12:"post_content";s:2984:"<strong>Dr. Francis Fukuyama</strong> is a professor at Stanford Universityâ€”the Olivier Nomellini Senior Fellow at Stanfordâ€™s Freeman Spogli Institute for International Studiesâ€”and a longstanding observer of global political and economic issues, with a special emphasis on the development of democratic political systems around the world. He has previously taught at Johns Hopkins Universityâ€™s Paul H. NitzeÂ School of Advanced International Studies, where he was the Bernard L. Schwartz Professor of International Political Economy and director of the Schoolâ€™s International Development program.Dr. Fukuyama has written widely on issues relating to democratization and international political economy. His bookÂ <em>The End of History and the Last Man</em> has appeared in over twenty foreign editions, and his most recent,Â <em>The Origins of Political Order: From Prehuman Times to the French Revolution</em>, is a 2011 <em>New York Times</em> Notable Book and a <em>Kirkus Reviews</em>, and <em>Globe and Mail</em> Best Book of the Year. Dr. Fukuyama has served as a member of the Political Science Department at the RAND Corporation, from 1979-1980, from 1983-89, and from 1995-96. In 1981-82, and in 1989 he was a member of the Policy Planning Staff of the US Department of State, first specializing in Middle East affairs, and then as Deputy Director for European political-military affairs.Â In 1981-82 he was also a member of the US delegation to the Egyptian-Israeli talks on Palestinian autonomy. From 2001-2004 he served on the Presidentâ€™s Council on Bioethics, established by President George W. Bush. Dr. Fukuyama received his B.A. in classics from Cornell University and his Ph.D. in political science from Harvard University. From 1996-2000, he was the Omer L. and Nancy Hirst Professor of Public Policy at theÂ School of Public Policy at George Mason University. His other books includeÂ <em>America at the Crossroads:Â Democracy, Power, and the Neoconservative Legacy</em>, andÂ <em>Falling Behind:Â Explaining the Development Gap between Latin America and the United States</em>. Â Dr. Fukuyama is chairman of the editorial board ofÂ <em>The American Interest</em>, which he helped to found in 2005. He is a senior fellow at the Johns Hopkins SAIS Foreign Policy Institute, and a non-resident fellow at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. He holds honorary doctorates from Connecticut College, Doane College, Doshisha University and Kansai University in Japan, and Aarhus University in Denmark.Â  He is a member of the Board of Trustees of theÂ RAND Corporation, the Board of Directors of theÂ National Endowment for Democracy, and member of the advisory boards for theÂ <em>Journal of Democracy</em>, theÂ Inter-American Dialogue, andÂ The New America Foundation.Â He is a member of the American Political Science Association and the Council on Foreign Relations. He lives with his wife Laura Holmgren in California, and has three children.";s:10:"post_title";s:16:"Francis Fukuyama";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:16:"francis-fukuyama";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-03 16:37:48";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-03 20:37:48";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=250";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}}s:8:"col_info";a:23:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":